abstract: The clash has consequences beyond New York, going to the heart of a national debate likely to dominate the 2020 election: What is the best way to spread prosperity?
snippet: The clash has consequences beyond New York, going to the heart of a national debate likely to dominate the 2020 election: What is the best way to spread prosperity?
lead_paragraph: The political opposition that prompted Amazon to walk away from building a corporate headquarters in New York City featured a touchstone of the progressives’ economic agenda: ending tax policies that unfairly reward and pamper the wealthy.

headline_main: In Amazon Fight, Progressives Showed What They Want: A New Economic Agenda
headline_print_headline: Amazon’s Exit Reignites a Debate Over Growth

abstract: Candidates like Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders were quick to praise New Yorkers who rebelled at the idea of giving tax breaks to a huge corporation.
snippet: Candidates like Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders were quick to praise New Yorkers who rebelled at the idea of giving tax breaks to a huge corporation.
lead_paragraph: The decision by Amazon this week to abandon its planned headquarters in New York City tapped into one of the major themes of left-wing Democrats: that giant corporations — and in some cases the billionaires who run them — must be held to account for wage inequality, corporate greed and middle-class stagnation.

abstract: Politicians’ memoirs, including those by Joe Biden and Kamala Harris, can give insight into their values.
snippet: Politicians’ memoirs, including those by Joe Biden and Kamala Harris, can give insight into their values.
lead_paragraph: (Updated June 26) More than 20 candidates have announced a bid for the presidency, and many of them will lay out their policy positions on Wednesday and Thursday during the first Democratic presidential debate. Often, politicians release books pegged to their announcements to drive interest and give voters a chance to get to know them. Here is a guide to some of those books, which can provide insight into the candidates’ priorities and worldview.

abstract: Are billionaires a sign of a country’s health or weakness? Are they helping or hurting society?
snippet: Are billionaires a sign of a country’s health or weakness? Are they helping or hurting society?
lead_paragraph: In 2018, there were 585 billionaires in America, with a combined wealth of over $2.8 trillion. The wealthiest, Jeff Bezos, the founder of Amazon, has a net worth of $160 billion.

abstract: To accommodate the sprawling field, the party announced that it would hold debates in June and July on consecutive nights, dividing candidates by random selection.
snippet: To accommodate the sprawling field, the party announced that it would hold debates in June and July on consecutive nights, dividing candidates by random selection.
lead_paragraph: The Democratic National Committee on Thursday unveiled the criteria for participation in the first two presidential primary debates, splitting the debates across two consecutive nights to accommodate an already sprawling field of candidates.

headline_main: How Every Senator Voted on the Shutdown and Border Bill
byline_original: By Annie Daniel and Jasmine C. Lee

abstract: And in any case, Democrats are not planning to seize the means of production anytime soon.
snippet: And in any case, Democrats are not planning to seize the means of production anytime soon.
lead_paragraph: Only a handful of Democrats in Congress (and just one Democrat-adjacent presidential contender) identify as “socialist,” but they appear to be the chief targets of President Trump as he faces a confident Democratic opposition in the House of Representatives. “We are alarmed by new calls to adopt socialism in our country,” he said in his State of the Union address two weeks ago, declaring that “America will never be a socialist country.”
